00:12:00.719 --> 00:12:17.599
So, the first one is I'm on the conference committee for PositConf, and one of the things that we do a little differently at PositConf is when you submit a talk, you don't submit a title and abstract, you make a one-minute video.

00:12:17.599 --> 00:12:32.080
And as someone who, like, reviews, like, talks, that's, like, the best way to get a sense of, like, is this an interesting topic and an interesting speaker, like, that one-minute video gives you so much more information than an abstract.

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:37.679
On the downside, it's in this video form, which we can watch as humans, but it's much harder to analyze.

00:12:37.679 --> 00:12:45.479
So, like, this time, what I did is I used Gemini, and I'm not going to show you that here, but I used Gemini to get a transcript of every single one of the videos.

00:12:45.479 --> 00:12:51.719
And then what I wanted to do is take all those transcripts and try to figure out, like, what is this talk about?

00:12:51.719 --> 00:13:04.840
There's, like, a few buckets at PositConf we're kind of particularly interested in, like, what's the balance of talks about R and Python, then we know there's a lot of talks about reporting and Shiny and AI.

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:20.799
So, what I'm using here is this structured data extraction, which is a pretty common feature of most foundation models these days, where you give it effectively a JSON schema describing the data that you want.

00:13:20.799 --> 00:13:22.520
So, you don't just get blobs of text.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:25.520
You're going to get a nicely structured JSON output.

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:29.960
Here, I'm using the Elmer package, which is my package to do this.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:33.640
So, you can see I've got a talk object.

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:40.239
It consists of a summary, which I want to be a two- to four-bullet summary of the talk, and then a bunch of topics.

00:13:40.239 --> 00:13:47.239
So, is it about R or Python or teaching or community, and then give me a few keywords.

00:13:47.239 --> 00:13:53.520
So, then I'm going to use Google Gemini here, and then I'm going to feed it, basically.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:56.159
Let's see if this is going to work.

00:13:56.159 --> 00:14:03.039
I'm going to feed it all 300-and-something transcripts, so each of these is a separate.

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:10.200
Now, we cross our fingers and see if this works.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:13.200
Oh, whoops. It's still running the Shiny app I was using earlier.

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:16.880
Let's start that again.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:23.080
So, it's running my R code, and now it's sending all of those in parallel.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:24.840
I think this is pretty neat.

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:31.000
So, it's, you know, working through all, I guess, 200-and-something,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.599
and now I can find out how many tokens I spent.

00:14:33.599 --> 00:14:41.559
You know, that was a grand cost of 12 cents, and then I can turn it into a nice data frame.

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:49.320
If I do that, I think I can do a nice data frame, which tells me for each of these topics,

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:57.840
which is a major or minor feature, and then, like this, I do a little bit more data manipulation and turn it into a plot,

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:03.640
and this is just so useful for us as a program committee to get a sense of, like,

00:15:03.640 --> 00:15:07.520
what did people actually submit?

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:11.440
So, you can see, not too surprisingly, we used to be RStudioConf,

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:20.559
so a lot of talks about the majorly feature R, you know, lots of Python, lots of Shiny, quite a bit of AI.

00:15:20.559 --> 00:15:25.880
Sort of interesting, and I gave it this, you know, I think another good general prompting advice

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:31.080
is always give the model some explicit way to, like, opt out if it doesn't know what you're doing,

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:33.719
what it's doing, so I gave it this unknown.

00:15:33.719 --> 00:15:38.239
You know, every time I run this, the bar chart looks a little bit different,

00:15:38.239 --> 00:15:40.719
but that's kind of okay in this case.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:46.719
Like, what I'm mostly interested in, like, overall, like, on average, like, how are things looking?

00:15:46.719 --> 00:15:52.440
So, this kind of combination of, you know, LLMs, which are stochastic,

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:55.359
they give you slightly different responses all the time,

00:15:55.359 --> 00:15:58.719
and moving into this kind of more, like, statistical mindset,

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:02.719
where I don't actually care too much about the individual answers.

00:16:02.719 --> 00:16:05.280
I'm looking more about the averages and the trends.

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:08.520
That just feels like a really, really nice pairing to me,

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:15.719
and the ability to just, like, churn through all of this, like, text analysis so quickly.

00:16:15.719 --> 00:16:21.760
Very, very general tools, like, only really limited by my ability to write good prompts.

00:16:21.760 --> 00:16:25.400
Just feels, like, really, really cool and useful to me.

