00:21:38.319 --> 00:21:43.119
And so, this is generating R code or Python code, if you're so inclined.

00:21:43.119 --> 00:21:44.959
It's running that code.

00:21:44.959 --> 00:21:46.719
It's creating plots.

00:21:46.719 --> 00:21:52.920
It's sending the plots back to the LLM so that they can interpret it.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:54.439
It's creating summary tables.

00:21:54.439 --> 00:21:56.680
It's interpreting those.

00:21:56.680 --> 00:22:02.079
And it's just trying to help you do this whole sort of exploratory data analysis cycle of, like,

00:22:02.079 --> 00:22:06.719
looking at the data, generating questions, writing code to answer those questions,

00:22:06.719 --> 00:22:10.119
and iterate again and again and again.

00:22:10.119 --> 00:22:14.079
I don't see this as being, like, a replacement for the data scientists.

00:22:14.079 --> 00:22:21.040
But this is something that I think can really help you get up to speed with a new data set very, very quickly.

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:22.400
So, we've got just a couple of minutes left.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:24.800
So, we won't have any more time for you to chat.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:29.119
I just want to talk, again, you know, we've talked a little bit as a data scientist.

00:22:29.119 --> 00:22:31.079
I think a lot of your job is coding.

00:22:31.079 --> 00:22:32.199
A lot of your job is writing.

00:22:32.199 --> 00:22:34.959
And the rest of it is data sciencing.

00:22:34.959 --> 00:22:39.880
Coding, I think, in general, we've got a good handle on how you can use LLM to code.

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:41.599
Writing, we're still learning about.

00:22:41.599 --> 00:22:44.800
Data science, tons and tons of opportunities.

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:50.280
And I just wanted to finish with a few of the resources that I find most useful for keeping up to date.

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:55.680
Simon Willison does a great job of giving you just sort of a vibe check on the latest models.

00:22:55.680 --> 00:23:04.640
I really enjoy Ethan Mollick's Substack, which is data science-y, but sort of AI in general.

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:10.920
I just started following Hilary Gridley, who gives good advice for using LLMs,

00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:12.839
sort of more generally in the business.

00:23:12.839 --> 00:23:15.680
And then, finally, I love Lynne Cherney's Substack,

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:20.560
which is really about, like, weird and whimsical uses of AI and LLMs.

00:23:20.560 --> 00:23:22.560
Thank you.

